//| **Term**                        | **Description**                                                                                                                                                                     |
//        | ------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
//        | **Definition**                  | An array is a collection of elements of the **same data type** stored in **contiguous memory locations**, where each element can be accessed using its **index** (starting from 0). |
//        | **Key Points**                  | 1. Stores multiple values in a single variable.<br>2. Fixed size (cannot grow or shrink).<br>3. All elements must be of the same type.<br>4. Allows **random access** using index.  |
//        | **Syntax**                      | `dataType arrayName[size];`                                                                                                                                                         |
//        | **Example 1 (Integer Array)**   | `int arr[5] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};`<br>Access: `arr[0] = 10`, `arr[3] = 40`                                                                                                        |
//        | **Example 2 (Character Array)** | `char vowels[5] = {'a', 'e', 'i', 'o', 'u'};`<br>Access: `vowels[2] = 'i'`                                                                                                          |
//        | **Memory Representation**       | **Index:** 0     1     2     3     4 <br> **Value:** 10    20    30    40    50                                                                                                     |
